{"cursor":"50841","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\n\n''â The many-fruited Thyme moss]]\n\n'Chloroplasts' () are organelles found in plant cells and some other eukaryotic\norganisms. As well as conducting photosynthesis, they carry out almost all fatty\nacid synthesis in plants, and are involved in a plant's immune response. A\nchloroplast are a type of plastid which specializes in photosynthesis. During\nphotosynthesis, chloroplasts capture the sun's light energy, and store it in the\nenergy storage molecules ATP and NADPH while freeing oxygen from water. They\nthen use the ATP and NADPH to make organic molecules from carbon dioxide in a\nprocess known as the Calvin cycle.\n\nThe word chloroplast (ÏÎ»ÏÏÎ¿ÏÎ»Î¬ÏÏÎ·Ï) is derived from the Greek words chloros\n(ÏÎ»ÏÏÏÏ), which means green, and plastis (ÏÎ»Î¬ÏÏÎ·Ï), which means \"the one\nwho forms\".\n","linknr":1166,"url":"Chloroplasts","recorded":1362512551,"links":109,"instances":["biology","ubiquinone","biology","fluid","cell_biology","genetics"],"pdf":["http://www.alfskovgaard.dk/publications/Skovgaard1998.pdf","http://www.alfskovgaard.dk/publications/Skovgaard1998.pdf","http://www.bioscience-explained.org/ENvol1_2/pdf/ctDNAEN.pdf","http://www.bioscience-explained.org/ENvol1_2/pdf/ctDNAEN.pdf","http://www.botany.utexas.edu/mbrown/papers/hreso/h26.pdf","http://www.botany.utexas.edu/mbrown/papers/hreso/h26.pdf","http://rspb.royalsocietypublishing.org/content/193/1112/295.full.pdf","http://rspb.royalsocietypublishing.org/content/193/1112/295.full.pdf"],"categories":["Organelles","Photosynthesis","Endosymbiotic events"],"headings":["Evolutionary origin","Chloroplast DNA","Structure","Pathogen defense","Chemistry","Chloroplast division","Transplastomic plants","See also","Notes","References","External links"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/a/a4/Flag_of_the_United_States.svg/50px-Flag_of_the_United_States.svg.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb